TITLE: Array Handling in Query Replacements with Sequelize 7
DESCRIPTION: Arrays in query replacements are now treated as SQL arrays by default. The sql.list function can be used to convert arrays to SQL lists when needed.
SOURCE: https://github.com/sequelize/website/blob/main/docs/other-topics/upgrade.md#2025-04-09_snippet_18

LANGUAGE: typescript
CODE:
```
sequelize.query('SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ANY(:ids)', {
  replacements: {
    ids: [1, 2, 3],
  },
});
```

LANGUAGE: sql
CODE:
```
SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ANY(ARRAY[1, 2, 3])
```

LANGUAGE: typescript
CODE:
```
import { sql } from '@sequelize/core';

sequelize.query('SELECT * FROM users WHERE id IN :ids', {
  replacements: {
    ids: sql.list([1, 2, 3]),
  },
});
```

LANGUAGE: sql
CODE:
```
SELECT * FROM users WHERE id IN (1, 2, 3)
```

LANGUAGE: typescript
CODE:
```
sequelize.query('SELECT * FROM users WHERE id IN $ids', {
  bind: {
    ids: sql.list([1, 2, 3]),
  },
});
```

LANGUAGE: sql
CODE:
```
-- The bind parameter syntax changes depending on the dialect, they are represented here as "?"
-- As you can see, this produced 3 bind parameters, one for each value in the list
SELECT * FROM users WHERE id IN (?, ?, ?)
```

